from its first adoption unless: (i) the agency clearly
HB136 INTRODUCED
85 establishes it could not reasonably be foreseen during the
86 initial 120-day period that such emergency the immediate
87 danger to the health, safety, and welfare would continue or
88 would likely reoccur during the next nine months; and (ii) the
89 Governor certifies that the immediate danger to the public
90 health, safety, or welfare continues to justify the need for
91 the emergency rule. The adoption of the same or a
92 substantially similar rule by normal rulemaking procedures is
93 not precluded. In any subsequent action contesting the
94 effective date of a rule adopted pursuant to this subsection,
95 the burden of proof shall be on the agency to justify its
96 finding.
97 (3) Prior to indexing and publication, the agency shall
98 make reasonable efforts to apprise the persons who may be
99 affected by its rules of the adoption of the emergency rule.
100 An emergency rule shall be strictly construed and shall not be
101 valid except to the extent necessary to prevent, mitigate, or
102 resolve immediate danger to the public health, safety, or
103 welfare.
104 (c) It is the intent of this section to establish basic
105 minimum procedural requirements for the adoption, amendment,
106 or repeal of administrative rules. Except for emergency rules
107 which that are provided for in subsection (b), this section is
108 applicable to the exercise of any rulemaking authority
109 conferred by any statute, but nothing in this section repeals
110 or diminishes additional requirements imposed by law or
111 diminishes or repeals any summary power granted by law to the
112 state or any agency thereof.
